<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. To Permit JAL Charter Flight to Hawaii </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1703043794 Tokyo KYODO in English 0349 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1703043794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 17 KYODO -- The U.S. Government 
permitted Japan Airlines Co. (JAL) to operate a charter flight 
Thursday [17 March] from Sendai, northern Japan, to Hawaii after 
Washington delayed permission to JAL for regular flights on the 
route, the Transport Ministry said. Washington decided to 
postpone permission for JAL's weekly flights from Sendai to 
Honolulu, prompting protest from the Japanese airline which had 
planned to launch the new route on Thursday afternoon. 
  JAL immediately asked the United States to allow it to 
operate a charter flight to Hawaii to carry 275 passengers who 
already have booked the seats on the scheduled flight. JAL will 
use an airplane of its subsidiary Japan Air Charter for the 
flight to Hawaii. 
  Ministry officials said Wednesday that the United States has 
not given an explanation for the postponement of approval for 
the regular flights, but said it is probably a response to 
Japan's refusal to expand "beyond rights" for U.S. airlines 
flying to Japan that allow them to extend their routes to third 
countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

