<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Calls for U.S.-DPRK Talks Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2203101894 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0959 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2203101894 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, March 22 (KCNA) -- Leon Nzokene, general 
secretary of the Congolese Socialist Party, told the DPRK 
ambassador March 15 that the nuclear issue on the Korean 
peninsula should be settled through talks between the DPRK and 
the United States, the parties concerned. 
  He demanded that the United States withdraw the unreasonable 
preconditions. 
  Reinaldo Tefelvelez, first vice-chairman of the National 
Assembly of Nicaragua, in a statement March 8 said that if the 
nuclear issue on the Korean peninsula is to be settled, the 
United States must withdraw its nuclear weapons from South 
Korea, withdraw its unreasonable preconditions in the 
implementation of the steps of simultaneous action agreed upon 
at the DPRK-U.S. contact and sincerely approach the talks. 
  If the United States is really interested in dialogue, it 
must prove this in practice and stop the anti-DPRK campaign, 
first of all, he urged. 
  The French committee for recognizing the DPRK in a statement 
March 15 said the United States must not abuse the International 
Atomic Energy Agency and the international community for 
justifying its sinister policy of stifling socialist Korea. 
  The statement strongly demanded that the United States 
refrain from seeking a sinister political purpose with 
unilateral demands to the DPRK. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

