<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   KCNA Reports Local Industry `Booming' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2103152794 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1506 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2103152794 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, March 21 (KCNA) -- Local industry is 
booming in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea. 
  Over the past thirty years more than 2,500 local industrial 
factories have made their appearance throughout the country and 
their modernisation level improved considerably. 
  Foodstuff, textile, garment, paper-making and other local 
industrial factories, over twenty on an average, have been 
built in cities and counties which had only a few ones thirty 
years ago. 
  The Sakju foodstuff factory with a plottage of more than 
24,000 square metres has all its production processes 
streamlined. 
  The local industrial factories in Anju city now produce 
consumer goods of more than 1,420 kinds, or twice as many as 
turned out in South Pyongan Province in the initial period of 
the local industrial development. 
  The local industrial factories throughout the country now 
fully meet the material needs of the population by firmly 
relying upon the raw materials available in local areas. 
  There are more than 42,500 hectares of raw (?materiel 
cultivation) bases across the country, which produce over 8,000 
kinds of consumer goods. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

