<F P=100> Indonesia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Optimistic Over UNSC Seat </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2203034894 Jakarta Radio Republik Indonesia Network in 
Indonesian 0000 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2203034894 </F>
<F P=104>  Jakarta Radio Republik Indonesia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Indonesian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Affairs Minister Ali Alatas says 
Indonesia's candidacy for a non-permanent seat in the UN 
Security Council [UNSC] will face no obstacles as in previous 
years. Ali Alatas told reporters in Jakarta that there has been 
no opposition to Indonesia's current candidacy. Thus, Indonesia 
is not expected to withdraw its candidacy. There has also been 
no other candidate from the Asian group. He said Indonesia had 
the intention of becoming a UNSC non- permanent member since 
assuming the chairmanship of the Nonaligned Movement [NAM] in 
1992, as a NAM chairman is traditionally an UNSC non-permanent 
member for a two-year term. Indonesia failed in its bid in 1992 
because Oman representing the Arab countries asked Indonesia to 
withdraw its candidacy. Oman said it had been prepared for the 
post for a long time. Pakistan, which made its bid for a UNSC 
non-permanent seat, asked Indonesia to reconsider its candidacy 
in 1993. Indonesia is now confident that there will be no 
obstacles in its bid for the 1995-1997 term in 1994. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-6779 </DOCNO>
