<F P=100> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<F P=101> Malaysia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Chief on UNPROFOR Participation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2203113594 Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA in English 0946 GMT 22 Mar 
94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2203113594 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Butterworth, March 22 (OANA-BERNAMA) -- Malaysia is 
willing to send additional soldiers to serve in the United 
Nations Protection Forces (UNPROFOR) in Bosnia-Herzegovina if 
requested to do so by the UN, Chief of Defence Forces General 
Borhan Ahmad said Tuesday. 
  He said, however, there had been no proposal yet to despatch 
extra peacekeepers to the war-ravaged country. 
  So far Malaysia's contribution in UNPROFOR was sufficient 
alongside the participation of soldiers from several other 
countries, he told reporters after launching the 13th air Thamal 
joint exercise between the Malaysian and Thai Air Forces at the 
Royal Malaysian Air Force (RMAF) base here. 
  Malaysia has sent about 1,500 soldiers to join the UN 
peacekeeping force in response to the atrocities committed by 
Serbs on Muslims in Bosnia. 
  Ten RMAF aircraft, including five F-5E jets and three OV-10 
reconnaissance planes, are taking part in the exercise, an 
annual series held on rotation between the two countries to 
strengthen cooperation in operational procedures. 

</TEXT>

