<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Citizens `Apathetic' to North Korean Threat </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2203061894 Seoul CHOSON ILBO in Korean 22 Mar 94 p 29 </F>
<F P=103> SK2203061894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul CHOSON ILBO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By So Kyo] </F>
  [Text] Following the North Korean delegate's absurd threat 
on the weekend of 19 March that "Seoul will become a sea of fire 
if a war breaks out," the North Korean Army began inciteful 
broadcasts through loudspeakers in the DMZ saying that "South 
Korean armed forces, point your guns backward [kokkuro]." 
Meetings are being one after another at the Chongwadae 
[presidential office] and the White House daily. Foreign and 
domestic news reports sound like a war would break out any time. 
  Surprisingly, however, citizens' responses are rather 
apathetic. With the 9.85-point drop in the composite index when 
the stock market opened at 9:40 AM [0040 GMT, 21 March], people 
said: "So people are shaken as expected." However, the 
predictions of employees at security companies were off the mark 
as stock prices rose shortly thereafter. Consequently, the 
stock market yesterday ended with the usual range of 
fluctuation. The so-called "North- related items," that should 
have obviously plunged if "Seoul is to become a sea of fire," 
showed no particular changes. 
  The same applied to travel agencies who are used to being 
swamped by heightened airline ticket sales and visa inquiries 
whenever North-South relations have gone awry in the past. 
Saying that "nothing has changed," Na Yong-sok, 39-year-old 
sales manager for Global Tours, said "I would rather have our 
business suffer than receive such telephone inquiries in the 
future." There has not been much shopping in bulk either. 
Chong Yong-kil, 37-year-old president of the Kwangmyong Ha-an 
branch of Nongsimga [a supermarket chain], said, "It seems like 
citizens don't see much likelihood of war as they haven't been 
buying in bulk." 
  The college scene is also quiet. Why are the citizens so 
unperturbed? Yi Hyok-chu, chief of the marketing department of 
Lucky Securities Co., assesses that, "It seems that people have 
developed their own sense of the international situation from 
the prolonged negotiations on the North Korean nuclear issue and 
that they are well aware of North Korea's situation." A member 
of Seoul National University's General Student Council 
commented, "The `Seoul sea of fire theory' is merely North 
Korea's gesture to secure an advantageous position in nuclear 
negotiations." 
  Meanwhile, the Ministry of National Defense views this 
phenomenon from two contradictory positions -- that "it reflects 
a maturity in people's views," and that "it reflects that people 
have become desensitized to the security issue." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-6795 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas055_d_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-055 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister, U.S. Envoy Meet on Security </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2203012094 Seoul YONHAP in English 0109 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2203012094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 22 (YONHAP) -- South Korea and the 
United States held high-level security consultations in Seoul to 
discuss defensive missile deployment and joint military 
maneuvers, officials here said Tuesday. 
  Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu and U.S. Ambassador to Seoul 
James Laney led the talks held over breakfast. Gen. Gary Luck, 
chief commander of the UN Forces, and Kim Sam-hun, chief aide to 
Han on nuclear affairs, also attended, officials said. 
  The meeting was arranged just after the International Atomic 
energy agency (IAEA) adopted a resolution referring the North 
Korean issue to the UN Security Council. 
  Inside sources said Seoul and Washington reaffirmed the 
early 
deployment of Patriot missiles, 36 of them sometime next month. 
The two sides, however, held off on a Team Spirit decision 
while agreeing that the drill will be staged when deemed 
necessary, they said. 
  They also discussed what to expect at the UN Security 
Council 
once it takes up the North Korean issue, the possibility and 
effectiveness of sanctions, and Seoul and Washington's readiness 
to counter any North Korean threat, sources said. 

</TEXT>

