<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reports Units' `Defensive Posture' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2203095694 Seoul TONG-A ILBO in Korean 22 Mar 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> SK2203095694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul TONG-A ILBO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Ha Chun-u: "Frontline Military Units Assume </F>
Emergency Posture"] 
  [Excerpt] The North Korean delegation said on 19 March 
that "Seoul would be submerged in a sea of fire." These remarks 
have made the South Korean frontline military units become alert 
to North Korea's movements. 
  Yi Yang-ho, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, attended 
a 
meeting of security-related ministries chaired by President Kim 
Yong-sam on 21 March. In the meeting President Kim Yong-sam 
ordered them to assume a full defensive posture against North 
Korea. Although there is no sign of unusual military movements 
by North Korea along the Military Demarcation Line, including 
its large-scale military mobilization exercise, voices 
denouncing South Korea through loudspeakers have been further 
intensified. 
  According to the military operational plans of each Army 
unit, our officers and soldiers have intensified their awareness 
of North Korea, have continued to conduct battalion-level 
military exercises, and have fully maintained a military 
defensive posture. When President Kim Yong-sam begins his 
foreign trips on 24 March, the South Korean Armed Forces will 
assume the emergency defensive posture as was done in the past. 
Therefore, the South Korean Armed Forces will be more acutely 
strained than ever before. 
  This atmosphere is more clearly disclosed by the holding of 
situational meetings by each Army division on the front line, 
which were held for the first time since the North Korean 
delegation made such provocative remarks. [passage omitted on a 
meeting of division staffs chaired by the division commander] 

</TEXT>

