<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Not To Accompany Kim to Tokyo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2203012394 Seoul THE KOREA HERALD in English 22 Mar 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> SK2203012394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul THE KOREA HERALD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu will not accompany 
President Kim Yong-sam on his forthcoming visit to Tokyo this 
weekend in order to handle the North Korean nuclear matter at 
home, an official said yesterday. 
  The minister will, however, join the President during his 
Beijing trip scheduled for early next week, he said. 
  The official said Han Sunday suggested that he would rather 
stay in Seoul this weekend, which may be a critical point in the 
future development of the North Korean nuclear issue. 
  He said the international community is expected to move 
toward taking some kind of measures against North Korea this 
week, The U.N. Security Council may convene to hear reports from 
the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) on the results of 
its recent inspection of North Korean nuclear facilities. 
  The official said Minister Han might have felt that it would 
be more convenient for him to hold consultations at home with 
the United States and other countries on their joint strategy to 
persuade Beijing to join international measures against North 
Korea prior to his China visit next week. 

</TEXT>

