<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa `Gravely Concerned' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2203034994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0333 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2203034994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 22 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa instructed cabinet ministers Tuesday "to keep up with 
developments for seven to 10 days" over the suspected nuclear 
arms development by North Korea, government officials said. 
  The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) adopted a 
resolution Monday to refer Pyongyang's refusal of full 
inspections of its nuclear facilities to the United Nations 
Security Council. 
  Hosokawa said he was gravely concerned over the situation 
and 
was keeping it under close observation, the officials said. 
  Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura said in a 
separate 
press meeting that government ministries and agencies have 
started considering possible punitive measures against North 
Korea in preparation for the possibility of the United Nations 
Security Council adopting sanctions. Takemura also said it is 
important to exchange information with the United States and 
South Korea over the issue. 
  As for the large-scale transfer of goods and funds to North 
Korea by pro-Pyongyang Korean residents in Japan, government 
sources said it would be difficult to suspend such remittances 
even if sanctions were imposed. The sources said, however, that 
the government would consider the remittance issue. 
  The sources also said that Japan will have to take a harder 
stand toward North Korea since it is likely Pyongyang would 
target Japan if it develops nuclear bombs. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

