<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ways Studied To Halt Money Flow to DPRK </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2203105494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1045 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2203105494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 22 KYODO -- Government officials met 
unofficially Tuesday [22 March] to start discussing possible 
measures to halt the flow of Japanese money to North Korea, 
which allegedly funds a suspected nuclear arms development 
program. 
  The officials are considering banning cash remittances, 
grounding North Korea-bound sea vessels and aircraft, conducting 
export checks at Niigata on the Sea of Japan and refusing to 
issue reentry permits to travelers going to the isolated 
socialist state, government sources said. 
  North Korea denies that it is trying to build an atomic bomb 
but continues to deny international inspectors access to its 
more suspicious facilities. On Monday, the UN nuclear monitor 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) urged Pyongyang to 
comply with its safeguard measures and referred the issue to the 
UN Security Council, which could impose sanctions. 
  Analysts have suggested that the sanctions would have little 
effect on the already impoverished nation, which receives 
backing from China and an estimated 60 billion yen annually from 
pro-Pyongyang Korean residents in Japan. 
  Attempts to halt the money flow are likely to be thwarted by 
a confusing array of routes the money takes through banks, in 
cash, in trade transactions and through third nations on its 
journey from Japan to North Korea. Some is sent to relatives of 
Korean residents living in Japan but the U.S. insists the money 
is being used to fund the alleged arms program. 
  If sanctions are imposed, the government intends to do what 
it can within the limits of the law but worries about 
remittances making their way to Pyongyang through third nations, 
informed sources said. 
  Government sources suggested the Security Council will 
likely 
seek a way for the inspectors to complete the inspections in 
North Korea and is not immediately discussing a resolution on 
sanctions. 
  The sources said Japan intends to keep close contacts with 
the U.S., China and South Korea in an attempt to reach a 
peaceful resolution to the nuclear problem through dialogue. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

