<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fujii: Market Package Lacks Macroeconomic Steps </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2203024694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0227 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2203024694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 22 KYODO -- Permanent tax cuts and 
other macroeconomic measures will not feature in Japan's 
market-opening package to be unveiled this month, Finance 
Minister Hirohisa Fujii suggested Tuesday [22 March]. "I don't 
think such measures were spelled out," he said of the 
government's decision on February 25 to compile the package of 
measures to address the Japan-U.S. trade disputes. 
  Fujii was speaking at a regular press conference after a 
morning cabinet meeting. 
  "The centerpiece will be the four key measures and the 
actions in three priority areas" of the stalled trade framework 
talks with the United States, Fujii said. 
  His comments in effect ruled out recent remarks by Chief 
Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura calling for inclusion of 
tax and other macroeconomic measures in the forthcoming package. 
  The four key measures cited are deregulation, boosting 
imports, facilitating competition through stronger enforcement 
of the antimonopoly law, and expanding government procurement. 
  The three "framework" priority areas are insurance, 
automobile and auto parts, and government procurement of 
telecommunications and medical equipment. 
  Fujii has repeatedly told the U.S. side that Japan would 
conduct a "full-fledged" tax reform, including permanent tax 
cuts, as the ruling coalition has vowed to do so by the end of 
the year. 
  He has also repeatedly said that the latest 15.25 trillion 
yen stimulus package would put the economy on the path of 
full-scale recovery in the coming fiscal year. 
  Fujii said he and U.S. Treasury Secretary Lloyd Bentsen 
agreed to tackle bilateral trade talks in a "cooperative mood as 
we did at the APEC meeting." The finance minister and Bentsen 
held talks on Friday in Hawaii ahead of a two-day meeting there 
of finance ministers of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation 
(APEC) forum. 
  Fujii stressed, "the greatest importance for the government 
is to clearly show its voluntary measures this month." 
  U.S. officials have indicated that the U.S. would assess the 
possibility of resuming the stalled framework talks after 
reviewing the market-opening package Japan promised to compile 
by the end of this month. 
  On increasing international tension involving North Korea's 
nuclear issue, Fujii said his ministry will follow the 
government's decision in line with any United Nations 
resolution. He was referring to possible suspension of bank 
remittances from Japan to North Korea if the UN decides on trade 
sanctions against Pyongyang. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

