<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Transport Minister Criticizes Car Import Method </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2203054994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0537 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2203054994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 22 KYODO -- Transport Minister Shigeru 
Ito criticized the Trade Ministry Tuesday [22 March] for taking 
a different approach on the import procedures of automobiles 
that are often criticized by other countries as a nontariff 
trade barrier. 
  The Ministry of International Trade and Industry is simply 
making "noise" and trying to "lighten its load," Ito said at a 
regular press meeting. He was reacting to recent moves by the 
Trade Ministry calling for relaxation of automotive import 
procedures. 
  Japan sets detailed and stringent standards on car 
mechanisms, especially concerning emissions and safety, and 
requires inspection of every unit. Approvals called "type 
certificates" are issued for volume imports of individual models. 
  The Transport Ministry, which is responsible for enforcing 
the procedures, assumes the attitude that accusations by Japan's 
trade partners that the system constitutes a trade barrier 
derive from a lack of information. 
  As part of an effort to ease such criticism, the ministry 
sent officials to Detroit earlier this month to explain their 
position and provide information. 
  The Trade Ministry, however, has criticized the system 
itself 
as having problems, such as a long time required to get through 
the entire import process. 

</TEXT>

