<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Economy Reportedly Shrank in Last Quarter `93 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2203071794 Tokyo KYODO in English 0654 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2203071794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 22 KYODO -- Japan's economy shrank an 
inflation-adjusted 0.6 percent in the October-December period 
from the preceding quarter, or at an annual pace of 2.2 percent, 
the Economic Planning Agency said in a preliminary report 
Tuesday. 
  Domestic demand contributed to pushing up the gross domestic 
product (GDP) by 0.0 percentage point and external demand to 
depressing it by 0.6 percentage point, the agency said. 
Consumer spending, one of the prime engines of domestic demand, 
rose 0.7 percent from the previous quarter, while another 
pillar, corporate capital spending, declined 3.5 percent. 
  Meanwhile, Japan's real or inflation-adjusted gross national 
product (GNP) during the quarter shrank 0.4 percent from the 
quarter before, or an annualized 1.6 percent. 
  GDP and GNP represent the total output of goods and 
services, 
with the GDP excluding net income from abroad. Starting with 
the previous quarter, the agency switched its emphasis from GNP 
to GDP to assess the nation's economic performance more 
accurately in line with international trends. 

</TEXT>

