<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   LDP Agrees To Partly End Diet Boycott </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2203152394 Tokyo KYODO in English 1439 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2203152394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 22 KYODO -- The No. 1 opposition 
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) ended part of its Diet boycott 
Tuesday [22 March], agreeing to enact a set of 16 bills and a 
fiscal 1994 stopgap budget by the end of this month, officials 
said. Parliamentary strategists from the coalition and 
opposition camps reached the accord in a meeting. 
  The 16 bills are mostly budget-related ones. The provisional 
budget, which is expected to total around 11 trillion yen, 
covers government spending in the initial 50 days of fiscal 1994 
starting April 1. 
  However, the LDP refused to comply with a coalition request 
to launch deliberations on the 73.08 trillion yen full budget 
for fiscal 1994 by the House of Representatives Budget 
Committee, the officials said. The prospect for the opening of 
the key parliamentary committee session has remained uncertain, 
they said. 
  During the day's meeting of parliamentary strategists, the 
coalition asked the LDP to accept their proposal to allow the 
cabinet to explain the new state budget before the committee, 
they said. Sadatoshi Ozato, chairman of the LDP Diet Affairs 
Committee rejected the request, renewing an LDP demand that 
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa provide more information about 
his 100 million yen loan from the scandal-tainted Sagawa Kyubin 
trucking group. 
  Meanwhile, Hosokawa again turned down the opposition demand 
to submit documents that would corroborate his claims that he 
repaid the 100 million yen loan from Sagawa Kyubin Co. Hosokawa 
told reporters at his official residence, "there is nothing I 
can do" to comply with the LDP's demand to see the financial 
documents on the Sagawa loan to help revive parliamentary 
discussion on the fiscal 1994 budget bill. 
  Neither would Hosokawa bend on his earlier refusal to 
arrange 
for his former financial secretary, Masatoshi Miyama, to appear 
before the Diet committee to testify concerning LDP allegations 
that Hosokawa accepted the money as an unreported political 
donation. 
  Sagawa Kyubin was at the center of a 1992-1993 money-and-mob 
scandal which involved now retired LDP power broker Shin 
Kanemaru and former Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita. 

</TEXT>

