<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa Stresses Tokyo Lead in Disarmament </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1903111794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1040 GMT 19 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1903111794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 19 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa said Saturday [19 March] that Japan should take the 
initiative in leading world disarmament in a videotaped message 
to this year's alumni of the Defense Academy. 
  Hosokawa delivered the message by videotape since he cannot 
attend the Defense Academy graduation ceremony on Sunday due to 
his visit to China which started Saturday. 
  "We must lead disarmament...in the world," Hosokawa said. 
  It is unusual for a prime minister to stress disarmament in 
a 
message to graduates of the Defense Academy, defense sources 
said. 
  Hosokawa, pointing out drastic changes in the international 
situation following the end of the Cold War, also called for 
fresh ideas regarding the nation's defense program. 
  It is the first time that a prime minister will not attend a 
Defense Academy graduation since 1978, when then prime Minister 
Takeo Fukuda failed to attend because of illness. 

</TEXT>

