<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Takemura, DA Chief Urge Defense Policy Review </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2003030394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0223 GMT 20 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2003030394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Yokosuka, Kanagawa Pref. [prefecture], March 20 
KYODO -- Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura on Sunday 
[20 March] told the graduating class of the National Defense 
Academy that Japan should reconsider its defense policies in the 
post-cold war world. 
  "Considering the changes in the international situation 
since 
the end of the cold war and the remarkable progress in science 
and technology, it is important, with regard to the way the 
defensive strength of our nation should be, that the government 
indicate a new fundamental thinking," Takemura said. 
  Takemura spoke on behalf of Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa, 
who has been in China for a three-day official visit since 
Saturday. 
  Defense Agency [DA] chief Kazuo Aichi also said Japan must 
have a more divergent way of thinking than in the past on the 
defense of the nation in the post-cold war era. 
  "The role of the Self-Defense Forces which positively 
contributes to the peace and stability of the world through the 
United Nations will continue to grow larger," said Aichi, 
indicating a future increase in Japan's participation in U.N. 
peacekeeping operations. 

</TEXT>

