<F P=100> AUSTRALASIA </F>
<F P=101> Australia </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Congress Said Stalling on Uruguay Round </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2003132494 Melbourne Radio Australia in English 1100 GMT 
20 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2003132494 </F>
<F P=104>  Melbourne Radio Australia </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Australia has expressed its concern over the 
apparent stalling by the American Congress in implementing 
legislation necessary to complete the much-delayed Uruguay Round 
of world trade negotiations. The Australian treasurer, Ralph 
Willis, says he raised the matter during a meeting in Honolulu 
with the American treasury secretary, Mr. Lloyd Bentsen. He 
said he received an assurance that the legislation would 
definitely be passed by July next year. The two men were in 
Honolulu for the inaugural meeting of finance ministers of the 
Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation Forum. Mr. Willis also said 
that during the meeting some countries made it clear they were 
not going to be pushed into too rapid liberalization of their 
capital markets. 
  [Begin Willis recording] The Malaysians, for instance, have 
made it clear that they believe they had already opened their 
capital markets considerably and that they were concerned that 
if they simply abandoned all control in the banking industry, 
for instance, they could (?simply) be (?flooded) by foreign 
capital. So, there is no arguing about the direction of change; 
it was rather concerns being expressed by some of the developing 
countries about the points at which they could cope with the 
current liberalization of their economy. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

