<F P=100> AUSTRALASIA </F>
<F P=101> Cook Islands </F>
<H3> <TI>   Henry Urged To Take Firm Stand on Tax Haven </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1903141594 Melbourne Radio Australia in English 0500 GMT 
19 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1903141594 </F>
<F P=104>  Melbourne Radio Australia </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Cook Islands prime minister, Sir Geoffrey 
Henry, has been urged to take a firmer stand over allegations 
that Cook Islands is using its tax haven to defraud other 
nations. 
  The call has come from the Cook Islands high commissioner to 
Australia, Vincent Ingram, who has warned the allegations could 
severly affect the country. 
  Mr. Ingram has returned to Rarotonga to advise Sir Geoffrey 
on the issue. He said he has told the prime minister to take a 
more interventionist approach to the matter. 
  The allegations were made earlier this week by the New 
Zealand parliamentarian, Winston Peters. Mr. Peters told the 
New Zealand parliament that Cook Islands Government was 
operating financial scams worth millions of dollars. He tabled 
documents he said supported his claims. 
  Reports from Rarotonga say that today, Sir Geoffrey has said 
he will not look at the documents and he has denied any 
wrongdoing. 

</TEXT>

