<H3> <TI>   Mahathir Hopes DPRK To Allow Inspection </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2203103294 Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA in English 0914 GMT 22 Mar 
94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2203103294 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kuala Lumpur, March 22 (OANA-BERNAMA) -- Dr. 
Mahathir Mohamed hopes North Korea will allow United Nations 
officials to inspect its nuclear sites, currently a subject of 
tension between the two Koreas. 
  The prime minister, however, suggested that an appropriate 
approach should be adopted to facilitate the inspection. The 
approach must be one where they (North Koreans) must not feel 
they are being ordered to do this and that, he [words 
indistinct] comment on the current stand-off between North and 
South Korea on the nuclear issue. 
  South Korea Monday said it would resume preparations for war 
games with the United States in the face of a renewed threat 
from the North's to withdraw from a global pact limiting the 
spread of nuclear arms. 
  Speaking to reporters at the 10th International General 
Meeting of the Pacific Economic Cooperation Council here, Dr. 
Mahathir said he did not think North Korea wanted to have a 
nuclear war. 
  I don't think they want to have a war at all, he said. 

</TEXT>

