<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cabinet Instructed To Prepare for Emergency </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2203074494 Seoul YONHAP in English 0729 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2203074494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 22 (YONHAP) -- Japanese Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa instructed the cabinet on Tuesday to prepare 
for an emergency as the United Nations Security Council ponders 
economic sanctions against North Korea. 
  Hosokawa told the cabinet that he is closely watching 
international efforts to deal with the North Korean nuclear 
dispute. He said, "President Kim Yong-sam is going to visit 
Japan from March 24, and we should keep an eye on the situation 
for seven to 10 days. We must make every preparation for an 
emergency." 
  Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura told a press 
conference in the morning that Japan should exchange information 
with South Korea and Japan and act prudently. He acknowledged 
that working-level officials are studying ways to restrict 
remittance by ethnic Koreans in Japan to North Korea and 
prohibit North Korean ships from calling at Japanese ports. 
"But now is not yet the stage for the government to officially 
confirm that," he said. 
  On the military front, Defense Minister Kazuo Aichi 
instructed the Self-Defense Forces to reinforce security as 
tension rises in Northeast Asia. 
  Aichi told the press after the cabinet meeting that Japan is 
strengthening acquisition of information related to the North 
Korean nuclear dispute. 
  Tokyo is also preparing for a trade embargo in anticipation 
of a U.N. decision against the North Koreans. A senior 
government official said that in order to implement a 
full-fledged trade embargo against North Korea, the government 
will need to revise the enforcement regulations of trade-related 
and other laws. The Japanese Government is working on such 
revision, he said. 
  It would be difficult to prohibit remittance to North Korea, 
he said, but "the government should take every possible step. 
We will try to decide on prohibition (of remittance) as soon as 
possible." 
  He emphasized that Tokyo should conduct itself in a cool 
manner because if North Korea has succeeded in making nuclear 
weapons, it is highly likely they will be targeted at Japan. 
  Meanwhile, Japanese police checked all areas where President 
Kim Yong-sam is scheduled to pass by or stay on his visit to 
Japan this Thursday [24 March]. The Japanese police plan to 
establish a special comprehensive security headquarters, and 
about 16,000 policemen will be deployed to beef up security 
around Haneda airport, the Diet and the guest house. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

