<F P=100> AUSTRALASIA </F>
<F P=101> Australia </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Informed of `Concerns' Over Inspections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2203064394 Melbourne Radio Australia in English 0500 GMT 
22 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2203064394 </F>
<F P=104>  Melbourne Radio Australia </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Australia has reiterated its backing for 
international efforts over North Korea's refusal to allow full 
international inspections of its nuclear sites. 
  Foreign Affairs Minister Gareth Evans says Australia 
supports 
any action the United Nations Security Council may consider 
necessary in the matter. Senator Evans told the Australian 
Parliament that this week's decision by the International Atomic 
Energy Agency to refer the matter to the Security Council is a 
measure of how seriously the internatioanal community is 
treating the issue. 
  Sen. Evans also revealed Australia had expressed its 
concerns 
directly to North Korea. 
  [Begin Evans recording] We sent a message to North Korea 
ourselves last Friday (?with the idea) to allow IAEA inspections 
to be completed as a means of restarting the dialogue process. 
Regretably, the DPRK has not so far seen its interest as 
apparently being best served by proceeding in this fashion, but 
we hope, as it has on previous occasions when the situation, the 
pressure that is being mounted and the attitude of (?IAEA) and 
the attitude of the international community is clear, that North 
Korea will consider its position. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

