<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Keidanren To Invest in Saudi Industries </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2203074194 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 21 Mar 
94 Morning Edition p 3--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2203074194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Keidanren [Japan Federation of Economic 
Organizations] will invest in Saudi Arabian small-to-medium size 
companies not belonging to the oil industry in an effort to help 
Saudi Arabia diversify its industries. As the first step to 
respond to Saudi Arabia's request, Keidanren is studying a plan 
to invest several billion yen in food, pharmaceutical, and other 
companies. Keidanren plans to coordinate the final details when 
its officials visit there in late April. 
  Through the financial cooperation of 112 major Japanese 
companies and Overseas Cooperation Fund, Keidanren established 
an investment company called "Japan International Cooperation 
Organization" [JICO] aimed at developing industries of 
developing countries in 1989. The present investment program to 
help Saudi Arabian companies will also be implemented through 
JICO. 
  Pharmaceutical and food companies, such as noodle-making 
companies, are most likely to be offered the investment. 
Originally, Saudi Arabia requested investment in auto makers. 
However, Keidanren thinks it will be difficult to meet its 
request because the amount of investment would become enormous. 
A Keidanren Secretariat official said that "if possible," 
Keidanren "wants to sign contracts" when its mission visits 
Saudi Arabia. 

</TEXT>

