<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cabinet Urged To Focus on Drafting Budget </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2203140394 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 22 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2203140394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 22 March Evening Edition] </F>
  [Text] "Restraint should be exercised over discussions on 
political realignment until the fiscal year 1994 draft budget 
has been passed." This summarizes a number of comments 
successively made by some cabinet ministers at their informal 
gathering following a regular cabinet meeting on 22 March, in 
their apparent efforts to put a check on discussions of 
political realignment issues. Recently, stepped up discussions 
have been noted among ruling coalition parties over such issues, 
including a plan by the Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] and the 
Japan New Party [JNP] to form a parliamentary group. 
  Home Affairs Minister Kanju Sato (of the Social Democratic 
Party of Japan [SDPJ]) was the first to begin making the 
comments. He first expressed concern about the fact that the 
Diet has remained idle for nearly two weeks, as it remains 
uncertain as to when the lower house Budget Committee would 
begin deliberations on the draft budget. He then asserted: "The 
government and the ruling coalition parties have been carried 
away with discussing political realignment issues day after day, 
neglecting the budget. This is one of the reasons the cabinet 
support rating has dropped." "In light of the current situation 
regarding deliberations on the draft budget, we should all look 
forward to the passage of the draft budget and the `higire' 
bills [bills with a time limit] and refrain from commenting on 
the political realignment issues," he added. 
  Construction Minister Kozo Igarashi (of the SDPJ) joined 
Sato 
and said: "This is a very important matter. Considering the 
trends in the public opinion poll, we should all strive to 
strengthen the (cabinet's) centripetal force." 
  Labor Minister Chikara Sakaguchi (of the Komeito) followed 
suit and said: "It is important to have the people understand 
that the cabinet is united." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

