<F P=100> Indonesia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nuclear Plant To Continue Despite Opposition </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2303092794 Jakarta Radio Republik Indonesia Network in 
Indonesian 0600 GMT 23 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2303092794 </F>
<F P=104>  Jakarta Radio Republik Indonesia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Indonesian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The planned construction of the Gunung Muria 
Nuclear Power Plant in Central Java will continue despite strong 
public reaction, particularly those from environmentalists. 
Jali Ahimsa, director general of the National Atomic Energy 
Agency [BATAN], said this to reporters after opening a meeting 
of a working group of Asia-Pacific atomic experts in Kuta, Bali. 
According to the BATAN director general, a lack of funds is the 
main obstacle in the construction of the Gunung Muria Nuclear 
Power Plant. However, he attached great importance to the use 
of nuclear power because Indonesia will need huge electricity 
supplies, particularly in Java and Bali, in the future. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

