<F P=100> INTER-ASIAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Proposal for ASEAN Arms Registry Rejected </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1603051894 Manila MANILA STANDARD in English 12 Mar 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> BK1603051894 </F>
<F P=104>  Manila MANILA STANDARD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Security and defense officials of countries on the 
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) have shelved a 
Philippine proposal to monitor conventional arms buildup and 
military expenditures in the region. They opted to determine 
first how a United Nations-sponsored arms register would fare 
out. 
  Foreign Affairs Undersecretary Rodolfo Severino, who 
attended 
the recent special ASEAN senior officials meeting in Bangkok, 
reported that ASEAN member-states have taken a cautious stand on 
the Philippine proposal since it was wider in scope than the 
existing UN arms monitoring mechanisms. 
  "More or less we felt that the UN arms register should be 
allowed to see how it works first," Severino said. 
  The UN arms register is limited to monitoring exports and 
imports of major weapons system such as missiles, tanks, and 
combat aircraft. The Philippine proposal includes the exchange 
of information among ASEAN member-states on the indigenous 
production of conventional arms systems and military 
expenditures. 

</TEXT>

