<F P=100> INTER-ASIAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pacific Economic Cooperation Council Meeting </TI></H3>
<H4>   Indonesian Minister on APEC Summit </H4>
<F P=102> BK2303143094 Jakarta ANTARA in English 0530 GMT 23 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK2303143094 </F>
<F P=104>  Jakarta ANTARA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kuala Lumpur, March 23 (ANTARA) -- Indonesia, which 
will host the informal summit of the Asia-Pacific Economic 
Cooperation (APEC) forum next November, has identified four 
areas of cooperation which may be intensively discussed during 
the conference, a senior minister has said. 
  Coordinating Minister of Industry and Trade Hartarto listed 
the potential areas of cooperation in a speech here Tuesday in a 
dinner party given to some 600 participants from 20 countries 
attending the three-day 10th meeting of the Pacific Economic 
Cooperation Council (PECC). 
  The PECC meeting began Tuesday. 
  The minister said that the four areas relate to the 
development of human resources, infrastructures, small and 
medium scale industries and the private sector's participation 
in economic cooperation. 
  Cooperation in the four areas, he said, will be concentrated 
on investment and regional trade, which will be implemented in 
conformity with the General Agreement on Trade and Tariffs 
(GATT). 
  "We believe that assistance and support from the governments 
of member countries will make APEC activities this year useful," 
he added. 
  According to Hartarto, the decisions to be reached in the 
forthcoming summit will have a profound global impact as APEC 
will bring together the East and West countries as well as the 
North and South nations. 
  APEC, set up in 1989, now groups 17 countries comprising 
Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore, Thailand, Brunei Darussalam, the 
Philippines, the United States, Canada, Australia, New Zealand, 
Taiwan, Hong Kong, People's China, South Korea, Japan, Mexico 
and Papua New Guinea. 
  The minister further said that the North-South dialogue and 
economic cooperation will take on a global scale once the 
dialogue and economic cooperation in Asia and the Pacific become 
successful. 
  On the first day of the PECC meeting, Hartarto talked about 
APEC problems, free trade areas and open regionalism. 
  He said that regional trade alliances is now a permanent 
part 
of a global trade system and that open regionalism is currently 
based on regional expansion and global trade. 
  Although designed to support local industries, regional 
trade 
alliance is by no means meant to discriminate against 
corporations from outside the region concerned, he added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

