<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Keidanren's Hiraiwa Discusses Economy, DPRK </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2403044194 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 24 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2403044194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From MAINICHI SHIMBUN 24 March Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] Gaishi Hiraiwa, chairman of Keidanren [Japan 
Federation of Economic Organizations], talked about economic 
prospects at a news conference on 23 March. He indicated: 
"While there are encouraging signs, my feeling is that economic 
recovery will probably come by the end of this year or in 
January 1995." 
  He also said: "There are still factors obstructing the 
recovery." He cited the following factors: 1) Land 
transactions remain stagnant, and the value of collateral 
remains low; 2) as long as Japan has a huge trade surplus, 
appreciation of the yen will continue; 3) corporate 
restructuring, for instance, in terms of capital investment and 
employment, has not been completed. 
  Hiraiwa further indicated a cautious view about talks on a 
further economic plunge. He said: "In March last year, it was 
said the recession had bottomed out, but there was a further dip 
in the April-June period. I think the situation has improved 
from last year, but we cannot yet say for sure the same thing 
will not happen this year." 
  [In a related 450-character report carried in its 24 March 
morning edition received via Nikkei Telecom Database, MAINICHI 
SHIMBUN also reports: "Hiraiwa commented on the International 
Atomic Energy Agency's (IAEA) nuclear inspections in North Korea 
at the same 23 March news conference. He said: `There should 
be several stages before imposing economic sanctions. As much 
as possible, it is necessary not to carry out sanctions and 
isolate North Korea.' He indicated that Japan should exert 
efforts in that direction. 
  "Hiraiwa further stated: `The DPRK's isolation will 
constitute a factor of uncertainty in world stability and peace. 
Through its traditional contacts, Japan should work to help 
North Korea adapt to the international community. At the same 
time, North Korea should also exert efforts to adapt to the 
international community.' 
  "Regarding economic sanctions, Hiraiwa said: `If that 
becomes necessary, it would be advisable to cooperate with other 
countries through the United Nations.'"] 

</TEXT>

