<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Coalition Parties Split on DPRK Sanctions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2303142294 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 23 Mar 94 
Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2303142294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] While the possibility of sanctions against the DPRK 
(North Korea) is becoming the focal point of the UN policy 
concerning that nation's alleged nuclear development program, 
the coalition parties are demonstrating discord over Japan's 
North Korea policy. The disparity in the parties' North Korean 
policies is likely to become a sensitive issue for the coalition 
government. 
  Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa is calling for following 
the 
international community if the UN Security Council [UNSC] 
decides on sanctions against North Korea. But some quarters in 
the coalition government are demonstrating a negative attitude 
toward "sanctions." In addition to the Social Democratic Party 
of Japan [SDPJ], which has long taken a pro-DPRK stand, some 
conservative coalition leaders such as Chief Cabinet Secretary 
Masayoshi Takemura and hajime Ishii of Shinseito [Japan Renewal 
Party], chairman of the lower house Special Committee on 
Political Reform, are prudent on this issue because they have 
been leading efforts to normalize Japan-DPRK relations. 
  In a 22 March news conference, SDPJ Chairman Tomiichi 
Murayama expressed a prudent attitude toward a hardline policy 
against North Korea in stressing the need for a settlement of 
the nuclear issue through peaceful talks. He said: "The issue 
must be settled between the United States and North Korea, for 
as long as this is a possibility. I think we should do 
everything we can to reach a settlement through consultations, 
rather than through immediate sanctions." 
  In contrast, Shinseito Secretary General Ichiro Ozawa said 
on 
22 March: "In line with the concept of the Constitution, Japan 
must secure its own peace, security, and presence under the 
global peace realized by the UN centrism. If we do not take 
actions according to this principle, the international community 
will not trust Japan." Thus, Ozawa noted his policy of 
following the UN decision even if it is an embargo. 
  Senior Shinseito officials are expressing concern about the 
internal discord in the coalition, saying, "We are not sure if 
the coalition can reach an accord when economic sanctions 
against North Korea become inevitable." However, a senior 
Komeito official is optimistic about this and says that the 
coalition parties will eventually get together on this issue. He 
noted, "Some SDPJ members will actually oppose sanctions against 
North Korea, but the party cannot withdraw from the coalition 
over this particular issue." 
  The coalition parties, however, have not had thorough 
internal discussions on their courses of action on the policy 
toward the DPRK. They will face difficult choices when 
"sanctions" become a reality. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

