<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK President, Delegation Pay Three-Day Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Tripartite Approach to DPRK Agreed </H4>
<F P=102> OW2403104094 Tokyo KYODO in English 1027 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2403104094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 24 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa and South Korean President Kim Yong-sam agreed in talks 
on Thursday to cooperate with the United States on the issue of 
North Korea's potential nuclear weapons capability, Foreign 
Ministry officials said. 
  Officials said Hosokawa and Kim, who arrived in Japan 
earlier 
in the day for a three-day official visit, expressed concern 
over the issue in which North Korea has refused to allow 
unimpeded inspections of its controversial nuclear facilities by 
the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA). 
  The two leaders also agreed that Japan and South Korea 
should 
construct a future-oriented bilateral relationship, while 
keeping in mind the dark episodes in their past history. The 
reference was to the Japanese colonization of the Korean 
peninsula from 1910-45. 
  Hosokawa and Kim discussed their respective experiences in 
implementing political reforms in their countries, the officials 
said. 
  Kim reportedly said if North Korea tries to buy time on the 
nuclear issue, there will be a limit to South Korean patience 
and it will be unavoidable for the international community to 
take a tough stance. 
  South Korea has prepared thorough security measures and will 
start this year's joint military exercises with the United 
States, code-named "Team Spirit," if Pyongyang does not change 
its stance, Kim said. He said he will make a concrete decision 
after his visit to China, which he leaves for from Japan on 
Saturday. 
  Hosokawa said it is imperative to leave open an avenue for 
dialogue with North Korea and to respond step by step. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

