<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK President, Delegation Pay Three-Day Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   ROK Parts Industries Agreement </H4>
<F P=102> OW2403112094 Tokyo KYODO in English 1058 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2403112094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 24 KYODO -- Japan and South Korea 
agreed Thursday [24 March] to work together to formulate an 
industrial program to foster South Korea's parts industries. 
The accord was reached during a meeting between Japanese 
International Trade and Industry Minister Hiroshi Kumagai and 
his South Korean counterpart Kim Chol-su, who is accompanying 
President Kim Yong-sam on his three-day visit to Japan from 
Thursday. 
  The joint program will feature acceptance by Japanese 
companies of South Korean trainees and dispatch of technological 
experts from Japan to South Korea. This is regarded as an 
effort to nurture small-sized South Korean companies, 
particularly "supporting" industries such as components makers, 
an official at the Ministry of International Trade and Industry 
(MITI) told a news conference. 
  Under the accord, to be endorsed at Saturday's meeting 
between Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa and Kim, Seoul will 
provide business incentives to South Korean parts makers through 
tax reforms and financial systems, the MITI briefer said. He 
said the program will be formulated so that it can be officially 
announced on May 26 when Kumagai and his South Korean 
counterpart meet again. 
  During Thursday's meeting between Kumagai and Kim, Tokyo and 
Seoul also agreed to cooperate on standards and certificates of 
industrial products and in insurance fields, the MITI official 
said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

