<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK President, Delegation Pay Three-Day Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Construction Ministers Meet </H4>
<F P=102> OW2403145994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1435 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2403145994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 24 KYODO -- South Korea's construction 
minister urged Japan Thursday [24 March] to allow South Korean 
contractors to participate in open biddings Japan plans to 
introduce from April for large-scale public works projects, 
government officials said. Kim U-sok, who is accompanying 
President Kim Yong-sam on a three-day visit to Tokyo from 
Thursday, made the request in a meeting with Kozo Igarashi, 
Japan's construction minister. 
  Igarashi said that Seoul has to join in a government 
procurements agreement under the General Agreement on Tariffs 
and Trade (GATT) and open its market before being allowed to 
make bids for Japanese public works. "If South Korea joins the 
GATT treaty and liberalizes its market, it will be treated like 
others," Igarashi said. 
  At the GATT-sponsored Uruguay Round of multilateral trade 
talks, completed in December last year, South Korea expressed 
its willingness to sign the government procurements pact, to 
come into force in January 1996. To do so, however, requires 
the country to liberalize its market first. The country has so 
far banned foreign contractors from making bids for its projects 
on their own. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>
